	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_882583" style="border-right: 1px solid #D1D1E1">
	
		
		
			<!-- icon and title -->
			<div class="smallfont">
				
				<strong>Progress vs. Risk Management</strong>
			</div>
			<hr size="1" style="color:#D1D1E1; background-color:#D1D1E1" />
			<!-- / icon and title -->
		

		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_882583">I have heard from many objective sources that we would be maintaining a human colony on mars right now, enjoying the fringe benefits of all the technology developed as a result. But a small and relatively insignificant number of accidents, as they relate to other worldly events, have all but halted any progress in space exploration&#8230;<br />
<br />
That is just one example of the topic, but there are many more. <br />
<br />
Take for example that some wild sci-fi sounding technologies that where originally the territory of private enthusiasts and underestimated visionaries, saw their greatest progress during the few moments in world history where &#8220;Progress&#8221; trumped &#8220;Risk&#8221;&#8230; Aircraft in WWI, &amp; Computers and Nuclear Science in WWII for example&#8230; Also the resulting Internet backbone and Space Program in the Depths of the Cold War&#8230;<br />
<br />
My question then is: <br />
<b>In your opinion, when is progress, if ever, more important then potential risk? And do you have an example why or why-not?</b></div>
		<!-- / message -->

		

		

		

		

		

	</td>
</tr>
