	<!-- open content container -->

<div align="center">
	<div class="page" style="width:85%; text-align:left">
		<div style="padding:0px 25px 0px 25px" align="left">

	<div id="edit882649" style="padding:0px 0px 6px 0px">
	<!-- this is not the last post shown on the page -->



<table id="post882649" class="tborder" cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%" align="center">
<tr>
	
		<td class="thead" style="font-weight:normal; border: 1px solid #D1D1E1; border-right: 0px" >
			<!-- status icon and date -->
			<a name="post882649"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/statusicon/post_old.gif" alt="Old" border="0" /></a>
			March 20th, 2006, 06:21 AM
			
			<!-- / status icon and date -->
		</td>
		<td class="thead" style="font-weight:normal; border: 1px solid #D1D1E1; border-left: 0px" align="right">
			&nbsp;
			#<a href="showpost.php?s=319eee47016bf22a7bf1e4bc59341a1e&amp;p=882649&amp;postcount=6" target="new" rel="nofollow" id="postcount882649" name="6"><strong>6</strong></a>
			
		</td>
	
</tr>
<tr valign="top">
	<td class="alt2" width="175" style="border: 1px solid #D1D1E1; border-top: 0px; border-bottom: 0px">

			<div id="postmenu_882649">
				
				<a class="bigusername" href="member.php?s=319eee47016bf22a7bf1e4bc59341a1e&amp;u=5495">Tangurena</a>
				<script type="text/javascript"> vbmenu_register("postmenu_882649", true); </script>
				
			</div>
			
			<div class="smallfont">Powered by Bacon</div>
			
			
			
			

			

			<div class="smallfont">
				&nbsp;<br />
				<div>Join Date: May 2004</div>
				
				
				<div>
					Posts: 2,925
				</div>
				
				
				
				
				<div>    </div>
			</div>

	</td>
	
	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_882649" style="border-right: 1px solid #D1D1E1">
	
		
		

		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_882649"><u>I'm going to recommend you read a couple books:</u><br />
<a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0691004129/" target="_blank">Normal Accidents</a> (strongly recommended)<br />
<a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0201479486/" target="_blank">Logic of Failure</a><br />
<a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0066620821/" target="_blank">Inviting Disaster</a><br />
<a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0262611465/" target="_blank">Sources of Power</a> (strongly recommended)<br />
<a href="http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/1585421391/" target="_blank">Trust Us, We're Experts</a> (strongly recommended)<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				In your opinion, when is progress, if ever, more important then potential risk? And do you have an example why or why-not?
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div> Normal Accidents covers this topic. Rather from the other angle: are there some technologies so unsafe, so risky, that no matter what the rewards promised, they shouldn't be allowed out.<br />
<br />
The first 3 books are about technology going wrong, and some of the reasons why. The 2nd and 4th books are about decision making, and how people make decisions under uncertainty. The authors of #4 did research for the US military for decisions &quot;under fire,&quot; so that the military could make better decisions in the limited time/fog of war situations. Among others, they studied fire commanders (the fireman in charge at fires), who is responsible for decisions about charging into burning buildings and how to fight the fire. He called his findings RPD (recognition primed decisionmaking). Most people don't use traditional decision making, the look at something and make a comparison with something they've seen before. As a result of Klein's research, the US military invests heavily in simulations and wargaming.<br />
<br />
People are very poor at making decisions under uncertainty. Which is why things like &quot;statistics&quot; are so counter-intuitive: they go against human nature/psychology. When interactions are far more complicated, the decision making gets worse and people who try to use logic to reason out the interactions get called flip-floppers.<br />
<br />
In addition, many people worship technology to the point it becomes an unassailable cult to them: the goddess of technology will save their devotees from disaster. Those fanatics not only refuse to see the risks involved in their worship, they get angry when someone else points it out. And they'll get even more angry when you point out that risks are borne differently by different social classes: the poor get screwed far more often by botched technology or accidents than the rich do. Because it is fashionable in the US to pretend that there are no social classes.<br />
<br />
We've been making petroleum refineries for the last hundred years. So you'd think we'd finally have a handle on why there are fires and explosions at them, and cut it out. But you'd be wrong. We've been making gravity dams for storing water for over 2000 years. So you'd think we'd finally be able to make them so they don't fail, since a failure usually kills lots of people and destroys much cropland. But again, you'd be wrong. We've been sailing ships for over 3000 years. So you'd think we'd finally make them so they don't fall apart in a storm, or crash into each other when they weren't on collision courses. But you'd be wrong. <i>FFS, dams are just piles of dirt, or nowadays, piles of concrete: they just sit there, how the hell can they fail?</i> You'd be surprised at the number of interactions between soil, dam and water. People can barely handle the number of interactions and observations involved in driving a car, and those interactions kill almost 40k Americans every year and injure far more.<br />
<br />
One of the points you'll get when you read Normal Accidents is that accidents are like a slot-machine. Most of them only pull up one cherry. You need to get 4 or more in a row to turn your factory into the next Bhopal. If the things don't line up perfectly wrong, you just end up with something that wastes time/money. Or only kills a few hundred people instead of thousands.<br />
<br />
Some technology is so complicated that accidents cannot be reduced below a certain level. Combine that with human foibles, and even that limit cannot be reached.<br />
<br />
One of my favorite pictures is of 2 side-by-side controls in a nuclear plant. They do very different things and in an emergency, if you pulled the wrong one, you'd make the situation worse. So the operators put distinctly different beer-tap handles on the 2 controls.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				In your opinion, when is progress, if ever, more important then potential risk? And do you have an example why or why-not?
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div> To give you three &quot;as simple an example as possible&quot; :<br />
<br />
1 - I point you to the differences in Europe and America over genetically modified plants. In the US, GMO are considered &quot;safe&quot; unless proven otherwise. In Europe, they're considered &quot;unsafe&quot; unless proven otherwise. Plants, via viruses and parasites, spread genetic information with different species (pollen is the normal method of gene transfer, and only works with closely related species). So it is possible for any gene inserted into a plant to spread to other plants. One need look at &quot;invader&quot; species to observe that a tiny advantage in surviving to reproduce will make plants and animals take over. And one can look at tent caterpillers and dandelions to observe how introduced species can become very harmful to native species. In Europe, they don't want to take those risks. In the US, the people who profit from such risks aren't the same people who suffer from the consequences, so they're busy pushing their choices on the people who will be paying for their misdeeds. My opinion on this subject is that while there can be great benefits from this technology, the people who end up paying for it are being considered externalities, so the cost/benefit analysis being used in the US is totally out of whack. The reluctance of the proponents of this technology to show that it <i>is safe</i> is interesting, since they're instead using politics to force their products on unwilling market/customers.<br />
<br />
2 - I point you to the role of tobacco in the US. For over 100 years, the tobacco companies knew their product was harmful. So they purchased false and misleading research to cover it up. The book &quot;Trust us, we're experts&quot; covers this and similar cover-ups. It took over 100 years from when the first research came out showing tobacco was harmful until the public was generally willing to acknowledge that the product was harmful.<br />
<br />
3 - Stem cell technology. Some religious groups believe that life begins at conception. Therefore, technologies that depend upon large numbers of embryos are evil and must be destroyed. These folks carefully ignore the huge numbers of fertilized embryos flushed down drains at fertility clinics. As a result, the US will lose out on any technologies based on stem cells.<br />
<br />
<br />
I don't have time to give you a shorter answer, and anyone with a &quot;quick and easy&quot; answer to this is trying to sell you something.</div>
		<!-- / message -->

		

		

		

		

		

	</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td class="alt2" style="border: 1px solid #D1D1E1; border-top: 0px">
		<img class="inlineimg" src="images/statusicon/user_offline.gif" alt="Tangurena is offline" border="0" />


