		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				The great risk was the act of the initial settlement, revolution, expansion, and government of a nation that was perched on the brink of failure, and consumption by an old world empire, several times before becoming anything remotely resembling the super power it is today&#8230; not to mention bailing out all of Europe not once, but TWICE in just the last century, while maintaining its own un-traditional concept of self determination, democracy, and trade.
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>The only risktaking I can see here was the initial settlement (which certainly took balls for the settlers, if not for the governments that sent them) and the revolt against Britain.<br />
<br />
Further expansion wasn't a risk, since there was no way in hell the natives could do anything about it. Governing a nation isn't that hard, and Britain's attempts to further destabilize and reconquer the US were halfhearted at best. Saving Europe wasn't particularly risky, since we joined the winning side late in WWI and since our impetus to join WWII was Japan attacking us first. Maintaining democracy isn't that risky, either - it works, we weren't exactly risking anything by keeping it around.<br />
<br />
I'm afraid I don't know where you're getting this supposedly risky behavior from.<br />
<br />
