	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_884014" style="border-right: 1px solid #D1D1E1">
	
		
		

		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_884014"><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>
					Originally Posted by <strong>Quin Haden</strong>
					
				</div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">My question then is: <br />
<b>In your opinion, when is progress, if ever, more important then potential risk? And do you have an example why or why-not?</b></div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>Risk can typically be minimized by time, waiting things out and acting cautiously instead of taking chances.  You can't eliminate all risk by giving situations more time, but you can substanitally reduce your risk.   Generally, the higher the degree of risk in terms of cost (human or money, whatever), the more time it takes to ensure a lower risk factor. <br />
<br />
So I would say that the matter depends on how important the progress is to do right now versus doing in a few months or years, etc.  And you have to weigh the potential gain of progress versus just keeping the status quo.<br />
<br />
As has been said in this thread already, you also have to weight the risk on in action as well as the risk of action.  In reports I prepare for various development projects, we analyze alternatives that are mostly different development configurations.  One of the alternatives we analyze is called the &quot;no project&quot; alternative.  That alternative is discussed in order that the risk of not doing the project at all can be assessed properly.<br />
<br />
An example/lesson might be the levees around NO and Katrina.   Sadly, although it appeared that there was a proper risk assessment made, there was little to no progress made to correct it.</div>
		<!-- / message -->

		

		

		
